        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10121F.xml">letter to W. D. Fox, 14 August [1875]</ref> (<hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 30, Supplement).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD first asked Fox about the correlation between deafness and the colour of fur and eyes in cats in 1856 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 6, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1895.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. D. Fox, 8 [June 1856]</ref>). The first two chapters of CD’s species book, composed in 1856 and dealing with ‘Variation under domestication’, are not extant, but CD later used much of the material for <hi rend="italic">Variation.</hi> He wrote: ‘The Rev. W. Darwin Fox informs me that he has seen more than a dozen instances of this correlation in English, Persian, and Danish cats’ (<hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 2: 329). See also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7952.xml"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 2d ed.</ref> 2: 322 n. 24, where CD cited Fox’s remarks in this letter.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Ryde is a seaside town on the Isle of Wight.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5687.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Frances Maria Fox</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6805.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George William Steward</ref>. Caister-next-Yarmouth (now Caister-on-Sea) was just north of Great Yarmouth, Norfolk.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
